``Mizushi Shrine'' is a {{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|Q161454|qid=Q161454|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Higashikagawa City|Q861255|qid=Q861255|1=Higashikagawa, Kagawa}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wataridayi Hyakushohime no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} is enshrined here. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and the old {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=Shakaku|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural company|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226|qid=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha}}. {{ill|lt=Sanukikuni|Q929682|qid=Q929682|1=Sanuki Province}}One of the 24 Shikinai shrines.

=== Enshrined God ===
; Main enshrined deity
* {{ill|lt=Watari-to-hi-momo-sou-hime-no-mikoto|Q11387098|qid=Q11387098|lt='''Watari-to-hi-momo-so-hime no mikoto'''|1=Yamato-totohi-momoso-hime}}

; precinct shrine
* Korei Shrine - {{ill|lt=Emperor Korei|Q313041|qid=Q313041|1=Emperor Kōrei}} (Korei Tennou) Behind the main shrine, the father of the enshrined deity.
* Kunidama Shrine - {{ill|lt=Wakoku Kahime|Q97539246|qid=Q97539246|lt=Wakoku Kahime no Mikoto|1=Jamatonokunikahime}} (Yamato no Kunikahime no Mikoto) Right hand side of the main hall, mother of the enshrined deity.
* Mizushu Sanzan (Kumano Sansha) Mountain worship It is said that Sojo Soun will be transferring the shrine.
** Shingu Shrine (Toramaruyama) - {{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|qid=Q682306|lt=Izanami Mikoto|1=Izanami}} (Izanami Mikoto)
** Hongu Shrine (Mt. Hongu) - {{ill|lt=Hayatama no Omikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Hayatama no Mikoto}} (Hayatama no Mikoto)
** Nachi Shrine (Mt. Nachi) - {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=jikaiotokoto|1=UNKNOWN}} (Kotosakao no Mikoto)
* Water Shrine - {{jalink|Mizuhanome|Q8191796|Mizuhanome no Mikoto} (Mizuhanome no Mikoto) Also known as the Elephant Goddess or Seoritsuhime.* Daisui-dera Temple (founding date unknown) Suishinushi Shrine Bettoji Temple. The principal image is Amida Nyorai (to Enko-ji Temple), Fudo Myoo, Nidoji (to Yoda-ji Temple), and Eleven-faced Kannon (to Sakate/Kannon-ji Temple). Suitokusan Hojuin Jingu-ji Temple was changed to Daisui-dera Temple during the Kanbun year. '''{{ill|lt=Saichō|Q449943|qid=Q449943|1=Saichō}}''', Enreki 9th year (at the age of 24), visited Suishupu Shrine and Daisui-dera Temple. '''{{ill|lt=Kukai|Q222227|qid=Q222227|1=Kūkai}}''' dug the Aka well water in the precincts and dedicated it to the shrine (currently the well of Yegadani). Until the end of the Edo period, Shintoism and Buddhism were mixed, and in March of the first year of the Meiji era, an order was issued to separate Shintoism and Buddhism, and on February 25, 1887, the temple was officially closed down.

=== Overview ===
; Outline
It is located on the right bank of the Yoda River, at the foot of a mountain near Ouchi Dam. It is also called Omizusushi Daimyojin. The shrine bush behind the shrine is a natural environment conservation area for Kagawa Prefecture, and the Inori cedar within the precincts has been designated as a preserved tree by the prefecture.

Many stone tools from the Jomon period and earthenware from the Yayoi and Kofun periods have been discovered in the vicinity, and there is also an ancient tomb on top of the mountain that is said to be the mausoleum of a princess, and the treasure trove contains many cultural assets. All of the shrine buildings are unified in {{ill|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|qid=Q3193781|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|1=Kasuga-zukuri}}, and the standing stone marking the shrine's territory still remains in Ouchi and Shiratori-cho.

According to the shrine's legend, the enshrined deity, Hyakushohime Wakatsubi, left the Kuroda Palace of {{ill|lt=Emperor Korei|Q313041|qid=Q313041|1=Emperor Kōrei}} when she was 8 years old, and was washed ashore here on a {{ill|lt=Tenban ship|Q126914107|qid=Q126914107|lt=Utsubo boat|1=Ama-no-iwafune}}. Hyakushohime was excellent at predicting the future, and she made it rain for people suffering from sunlight, taught them about water sources, opened waterways, and helped them grow rice. There is a mausoleum on the mountain behind the shrine.

; Shrine<ref name=":01">{{Cite web|Japanese book|title=Mizunushi Shrine |publisher=National Diet Library Digital Collection |url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/1227836/1/96 |website=dl.ndl.go.jp |access-date=2023-06-15}}</ref>* {{ill|lt=Jowa (Japan)|Q1075605|qid=Q1075605|lt=Jowa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}}3rd year (836) November 1st Jinshin (7th) Article "Sanuki Province Water Lord Deity Ceremony Consecrated to Jugoi" <ref>{{Cite web|Japanese book|title=National Diet Library Digital Collection |url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/1194459/1/56 |website=dl.ndl.go.jp |access-date=2023-06-15}}</ref>({{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|qid=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}})
* {{ill|lt=Jōkan (Japan)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} On April 9, 866, Mijo Mijo, the water lord appears to be the ``Junior Fifth Rank Sewer Lord God of Jusanuki Province''<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese book|title=National Diet Library Digital Collection |url=https://dl.ndl.go.jp/pid/991094/1/105 |website=dl.ndl.go.jp |access-date=2023-06-15}}</ref>({{ill|lt=Japanese Three Dynasties True Story|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|lt=Three Generations True Story|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}})
* {{ill|lt=Tenkei|Q1327340|qid=Q1327340|1=Tengyō}} 3rd year (940): After praying for the pacification of the pirates, he was promoted to the lower rank of Shogoi, and was further promoted to the rank of Shoichi ({{ill|lt=Chokan Kanbun|Q11651695|qid=Q11651695|1=Chōkan Kanmon}})
* {{ill|lt=Koyasu|Q1327182|qid=Q1327182|1=Kōhō}}4th year (967) "Sanuki Province {{ill|lt=Ouchi District|Q31478|qid=Q31478|1=Ōchi district}} Mizusushi Shrine" ({{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmecho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}})* At the time of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}5 (1872) {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, it was promoted to {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}
