; History<ref name=":01" />
* The reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Korei|Q313041|qid=Q313041|1=Emperor Kōrei}} (around 290 BC|Q28200}}) Kuroda {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Andomiya|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Watakutenhi Hyakusōhime no Mikoto|Q11387098|qid=Q11387098|1=Yamato-totohi-momoso-hime}} settled in Suishunushi at the age of 8 and was praised as the god of free water virtue.
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Bunmu|Q357246|qid=Q357246|1=Emperor Monmu}} 3rd year (699) {{ill|lt=Dainagon|Q1354706|qid=Q1354706|1=Dainagon}}{{ill|lt=Ishigamimaro|Q6086140|qid=Q6086140|1=Isonokami no Maro}} dedicates {{ill|lt=Emperor Monmu|Q357246|qid=Q357246|1=Emperor Monmu}} to our company and prays for the end of the epidemic
* {{ill|lt=Hoki|Q18520676|qid=Q18520676|1=Hōki}}1st year to 12th year (770-780) Reconstruction of the Gotare ruins
* {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}}9 (790) Dengyo Daishi, {{ill|lt=Saichō|Q449943|qid=Q449943|1=Saichō}}, at the age of 24, visited Suishinushi Shrine and Daisui Temple.* Around {{ill|lt=Honin|Q1373070|qid=Q1373070|1=Kōnin (era)}} (810-824), Kobo Daishi {{ill|lt=Kukai|Q222227|qid=Q222227|1=Kūkai}} dug a well of water in the grounds of Suishinushi Shrine and dedicated it to Suishinushi Shrine (it still exists in the grounds as the Well of Suishinushi).
* {{ill|lt=Tenryaku|Q1346281|qid=Q1346281|1=Tenryaku}} 2nd year (948) {{ill|lt=Doctor of Literature|Q11500074|qid=Q11500074|1=monjō hakase}} Tachibana Naoki goes as {{ill|lt=Imperial Envoy|Q11399920|qid=Q11399920|1=Chokushi}}
* {{ill|lt=Owa|Q1324768|qid=Q1324768|1=Ōwa}}2nd year (962){{ill|lt=Council|Q1133663|qid=Q1133663|1=Sangi (Japan)}}{{ill|lt=Tadasuke Fujiwara|Q11623 263|qid=Q11623 263|lt=Fujiwara Asaomi Tadasuke}} worshiped the {{ill|lt=Imperial edict|Q905765|qid=Q905765|1=Command paper}} and prayed for rain, and there was a proclamation, and the manor was called Ōsuinushi, and the name was called Ōsuinushi Taisha.
* {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q550527|qid=Q550527|1=Tenshō (Heian period)}} 1st year (1131) Visit of Sanuki {{ill|lt=Kokushi|Q1351234|qid=Q1351234|1=Kokushi (official)}} and {{ill|lt=Tsunetaka Fujiwara|Q134963520|qid=Q134963520|1=Fujiwara no Tsunetaka}}* {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q550527|qid=Q550527|1=Tenshō (Heian period)}}2 years (1132) {{ill|lt=Temple territory|Q11458058|qid=Q11458058|lt=Shrine territory|1=Jisha-ryō}} which was 2 towns, 2 tans and 60 feet became 24 towns and 5 tans. Around this time, there are records that {{ill|lt=Kokushi|Q1351234|qid=Q1351234|1=Kokushi (official)}} and {{ill|lt=Mokudai|Q11581544|qid=Q11581544|1=Mokudai}} frequently visited the shrine. It is believed that {{ill|lt=Temple territory|Q11458058|qid=Q11458058|lt=Shrine territory|1=Jisha-ryō}} was donated in the form of dividing a part of Yoda-go and Irino-go, which were Garyo|Q11421344}}. {{ill|lt=Shake|Q11588367|qid=Q11588367|1=Shake (social class)}} It reached the peak of prosperity with 75 members and 42 {{ill|lt=Sōbo|Q11387615|qid=Q11387615|lt=Sōbo|1=sangha residence}}. (Mizunushi Shrine Great Pannya Sutra Box Book)
* {{ill|lt=Chojo|Q1194264|qid=Q1194264|1=Chōshō}}2nd year (1133) {{ill|lt=Mokudai|Q11581544|qid=Q11581544|1=Mokudai}}Visit of Morimichi Kawachimae
* {{ill|lt=Chohiro|Q1193904|qid=Q1193904|1=Chōkan}}Visit of Sanuki Kokushi {{ill|lt=Hideyoshi Fujiwara|Q11623440|qid=Q11623440|1=Fujiwara no Hideyoshi}} in 1163
